 
Events represent a method for functions to be called when a certain action
takes place.  This action, we call an event.  The way events are represented
here on Darkwind is in a mapping, stored in each player object.  This mapping
has the event, the file to call, the function to call, and an optional 
arguement.  
 
So, to add an event for a particular player, you would do:
  this_player()->add_event(type, file, function, arguement);
  Where, type is a possible event type: login, logout, linkdeath and linkresume.
  File is the file to call and function is what to call in that file.
  The event handling routine will do:
    file->function(arguement);
 
To remove an event, use the same syntax:
  this_player()->remove_event(type, file, function, arguement);
 
You can also query all the events of a certain type:
  this_player()->query_events(type);
 
The types are listed in <events.h>.  Ask an implementor or supervisor for
a current list if you need an event that isn't talked about in this document.
 
WARNING: EVENTS ARE NOT STATIC! DO NOT USE CLONED
FILENAMES UNLESS YOU EXPLICITLY REMOVE THEM
BEFORE THEY ARE DESTRUCTED!
-Hayden 06/25/95
